---
import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Overview', level: 2 },
  { id: 'healthcare-system', text: 'Healthcare System', level: 2 },
  { id: 'visa-requirements', text: 'Visa Options', level: 2 },
  { id: 'insurance-requirements', text: 'Insurance Requirements', level: 2 },
  { id: 'recommended-providers', text: 'Recommended Providers', level: 2 },
  { id: 'costs', text: 'Expected Costs', level: 2 },
  { id: 'scenarios', text: 'Real-World Scenarios', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Italy Insurance Guide', href: '/countries/italy/insurance' },
  { title: 'Insurance for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors' },
  { title: 'Italy Elective Residency Visa', href: '/visas/retirement-visa/in/italy' },
  { title: 'Insurance with Pre-existing Conditions', href: '/insurance-for/pre-existing-conditions' },
  { title: 'France for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/france' },
];

const providerColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'entryAge', header: 'Max Entry Age' },
  { key: 'renewal', header: 'Renewal' },
  { key: 'monthlyFrom', header: 'From (65-69)' },
  { key: 'italyFit', header: 'Italy Fit' },
];

const providerRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', entryAge: '74', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: '$430-590/mo', italyFit: 'Excellent' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', entryAge: '74', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: '$380-530/mo', italyFit: 'Excellent' },
  { provider: 'BUPA Global', entryAge: '79', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: '$500-700/mo', italyFit: 'Very Good' },
  { provider: 'AXA Global', entryAge: '74', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: '$400-560/mo', italyFit: 'Very Good' },
  { provider: 'UniSalute (Local)', entryAge: '70', renewal: '80', monthlyFrom: '€80-200/mo', italyFit: 'Good (Local)' },
];

const costColumns = [
  { key: 'category', header: 'Expense' },
  { key: 'monthly', header: 'Monthly' },
  { key: 'annual', header: 'Annual' },
];

const costRows = [
  { category: 'International Insurance (65-69)', monthly: '$400-590', annual: '$4,800-7,080' },
  { category: 'International Insurance (70-74)', monthly: '$550-800', annual: '$6,600-9,600' },
  { category: 'International Insurance (75-79)', monthly: '$750-1,100', annual: '$9,000-13,200' },
  { category: 'SSN Enrollment (Voluntary)', monthly: '€400/year lump', annual: '~€400-2,000' },
  { category: 'Private Italian Insurance', monthly: '€80-250', annual: '€960-3,000' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Seniors in Italy | Retirement Guide"
  description="Guide to health insurance for seniors retiring in Italy. SSN access, Elective Residency visa, healthcare regions, and coverage for expats 70+."
  headline="Health Insurance for Seniors in Italy"
  subheadline="Italy offers la dolce vita with excellent regional healthcare—but navigating the system requires understanding both national rules and local variations."
  heroImage="/images/countries/italy-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Compare Senior Plans →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="overview">Why Seniors Choose Italy</h2>
  <p>
    Italy represents the dream retirement for many—world-class art, cuisine, and culture combined with a Mediterranean climate and affordable (outside major cities) cost of living. The Italian healthcare system, while complex, provides excellent care, and the quality of life is unmatched for those who appreciate history, food, and community.
  </p>

  <p>
    Popular retirement areas include Tuscany (expensive but iconic), Umbria (affordable alternative), Le Marche (coast and hills), Puglia and Calabria (budget-friendly south), Liguria (Italian Riviera), and Sicily and Sardinia for island life. Each region has its own character, costs, and healthcare administration.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Key Facts for Seniors</h3>
    <ul class="text-primary-800 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Healthcare ranking:</strong> WHO ranks Italy #2 in the world</li>
      <li><strong>Public access:</strong> Voluntary SSN enrollment available to residents</li>
      <li><strong>Regional variation:</strong> Healthcare quality varies by region (north generally better)</li>
      <li><strong>Language:</strong> Italian essential; English limited outside tourist areas</li>
      <li><strong>Cost of living:</strong> Varies dramatically by region</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="healthcare-system">Italy's Healthcare System</h2>
  <p>
    Italy's Servizio Sanitario Nazionale (SSN) provides universal healthcare, but it's administered regionally, leading to significant variations in quality and access. Understanding this system is crucial for choosing where to retire.
  </p>

  <h3>SSN Public Healthcare</h3>
  <p>
    Legal residents can enroll in the SSN, either through employment contributions or voluntary enrollment (iscrizione volontaria). Coverage includes:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Hospital care and emergency services (free)</li>
    <li>Doctor visits (small copay or free depending on income/age)</li>
    <li>Specialist consultations (with referral)</li>
    <li>Medications (varying copays based on category)</li>
    <li>Preventive care and vaccinations</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Voluntary enrollment costs approximately €400-2,000/year depending on the region and income declaration. Those over 65 are often exempt from many copays.
  </p>

  <h3>Regional Differences</h3>
  <p>
    Healthcare quality varies significantly by region:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Northern regions (Lombardy, Emilia-Romagna, Veneto):</strong> Excellent facilities, shorter wait times</li>
    <li><strong>Central regions (Tuscany, Umbria, Lazio):</strong> Generally good; Rome can be overwhelmed</li>
    <li><strong>Southern regions (Campania, Calabria, Sicily):</strong> More variable; some excellent hospitals but longer waits</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Private Healthcare</h3>
  <p>
    Private healthcare supplements the public system. Private clinics offer faster access and more comfort. Costs are reasonable:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Private specialist:</strong> €80-150</li>
    <li><strong>Private MRI:</strong> €200-400</li>
    <li><strong>Private minor surgery:</strong> €1,000-5,000</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Many Italians use the public system for major care and private for convenience items like quicker specialist appointments.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">The Language Factor</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      Italian is essential for navigating the healthcare system. Outside major tourist areas, English is limited. Doctor-patient communication works best in Italian. Many expats take intensive Italian courses before moving or hire translators for medical appointments.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="visa-requirements">Visa Options for Senior Retirees</h2>
  <p>
    Non-EU seniors typically use the Elective Residency Visa (Visto per Residenza Elettiva), designed for those with independent income who won't work in Italy.
  </p>

  <h3>Elective Residency Visa</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Income requirement:</strong> ~€31,000-38,000/year (varies by consulate)</li>
    <li><strong>Health insurance:</strong> Required—comprehensive coverage for visa</li>
    <li><strong>Work:</strong> Cannot work in Italy</li>
    <li><strong>Duration:</strong> 1 year initially, renewable for 2 years</li>
    <li><strong>Housing:</strong> Must show proof of accommodation</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Insurance Requirements for Visa</h3>
  <p>
    Italian consulates require comprehensive health insurance:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Coverage for entire visa period</li>
    <li>Comprehensive medical coverage (hospitalization, outpatient)</li>
    <li>Valid in Italy</li>
    <li>Minimum €30,000 coverage (though comprehensive expected)</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>EU/UK Citizens</h3>
  <p>
    EU citizens can move freely and access SSN. UK citizens post-Brexit need visas but can still access SSN once resident. EU retirees with S1 forms can access Italian healthcare immediately.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Need Visa-Compliant Insurance?"
    description="Find coverage that meets Italian consulate requirements."
    buttonText="Compare Plans →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="insurance-requirements">Insurance Requirements for Seniors</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance needs evolve through your Italian residency journey:
  </p>

  <h3>Phase 1: Visa Application</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Comprehensive international insurance required</li>
    <li>Must meet consulate standards</li>
    <li>Typical cost: $400-600/month for seniors</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Phase 2: After Arrival - SSN Enrollment</h3>
  <p>
    Once you have residency, you can voluntarily enroll in SSN:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Visit your local ASL (Azienda Sanitaria Locale)</li>
    <li>Pay annual contribution (~€400-2,000 depending on region)</li>
    <li>Receive tessera sanitaria (health card)</li>
    <li>Access public healthcare</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Long-term Options</h3>
  <p>
    After SSN enrollment, you have choices:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>SSN only:</strong> Public coverage + out-of-pocket private when needed</li>
    <li><strong>SSN + Italian private:</strong> Add UniSalute or similar for faster private access</li>
    <li><strong>SSN + international:</strong> Keep international for travel and higher limits</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="recommended-providers">Recommended Providers for Italy</h2>
  <p>
    These options work well for seniors at different stages:
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>For Visa Application</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Cigna Global, Allianz Care, AXA Global</strong> - All meet Italian visa requirements. Provide coverage letter for consulate. Plans with lower deductibles may be preferred by some consulates.
  </p>

  <h3>For Long-Term After SSN</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>UniSalute, Intesa Sanpaolo Assicura, Generali</strong> - Italian insurers offering supplementary private coverage. €80-250/month. Provides faster access to private specialists and clinics.
  </p>

  <h3>BUPA Global</h3>
  <p>
    Accepts applicants up to 79. Essential for seniors 75-79 who need visa-compliant coverage. Premium pricing but reliable. Can maintain after SSN enrollment for travel coverage.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Plans for Italy"
    description="Find visa-compliant coverage for your Italian retirement."
    buttonText="See Options →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  />

  <h2 id="costs">Expected Insurance Costs</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance costs decrease significantly after SSN enrollment:
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>Cost Evolution</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Year 1 (visa phase):</strong> International insurance ~$5,000-9,000/year</li>
    <li><strong>After SSN:</strong> ~€400-2,000/year SSN contribution + optional private €1,000-3,000/year</li>
    <li><strong>Seniors 65+:</strong> Many copay exemptions in SSN; lower out-of-pocket</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Cost-Saving Strategies</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Enroll in SSN promptly:</strong> Reduces costs significantly</li>
    <li><strong>Choose southern regions:</strong> Lower cost of living, lower SSN contributions</li>
    <li><strong>Use SSN for major care:</strong> Reserve private for convenience items</li>
    <li><strong>Over 65 exemptions:</strong> Apply for copay exemptions based on age</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="scenarios">Real-World Scenarios</h2>

  <div class="grid gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 1: Visa Application</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">George, 70, applying for Elective Residency from the US.</p>
      <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Gets Allianz Care ($520/month). Provides coverage letter to Italian consulate in Chicago. Visa approved after 6-week processing. Uses Allianz during transition period.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 2: After SSN Enrollment</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Carol, 69, settled in Umbria for 6 months.</p>
      <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Enrolls in SSN at local ASL (€388/year for Umbria). Gets tessera sanitaria. Registers with local medico di base (GP). Doctor visits now free. Cancels international insurance, saving €5,000/year.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 3: Hospital Stay in Northern Italy</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Robert, 73, needs cardiac procedure in Bologna.</p>
      <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Referred through SSN to Sant'Orsola Hospital (excellent cardiac center). Surgery + 1 week hospitalization. Total cost: €0 (SSN covers fully). Quality comparable to any European hospital.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 4: Private Specialist Access</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Martha, 71, wants to see dermatologist faster than SSN wait.</p>
      <p class="text-amber-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> SSN wait: 3 months. Uses UniSalute private insurance (€120/month) to see dermatologist privately within 1 week. Cost: €30 copay. Private insurance speeds access when needed.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 5: Southern Italy Healthcare</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Susan, 68, retires in Calabria for low costs.</p>
      <p class="text-amber-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> SSN enrollment easy; contribution lower than northern regions. Local hospital handles routine care. For hip replacement, gets referral to Rizzoli Orthopaedic Institute in Bologna (covered by SSN—can seek care anywhere in Italy).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 6: Senior Over 75</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">William, 77, applying for Italian visa.</p>
      <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Gets BUPA Global ($750/month)—one of few options at 77. Visa approved. After SSN enrollment, maintains BUPA for travel to visit grandchildren in UK. SSN handles all Italian care; most copays waived due to age.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I access the Italian public healthcare system?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">Yes, once you have legal residency. Visit your local ASL (health authority) to enroll voluntarily in SSN. Cost is approximately €400-2,000/year depending on region. After enrollment, you get a tessera sanitaria and can register with a local doctor.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Which region has the best healthcare?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">Emilia-Romagna, Lombardy, Veneto, and Tuscany consistently rank highest. Northern regions generally have better facilities and shorter wait times. However, you can seek care in any region—many southerners travel north for complex procedures.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to speak Italian?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">Strongly recommended, especially for healthcare. Outside tourist areas, English is limited. Doctor-patient communication works best in Italian. Many expats take Italian courses before moving. For complex medical discussions, consider a translator or bilingual friend.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">I'm 78—what are my options?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">BUPA Global accepts applicants up to 79. Once in Italy with residency, SSN has no age limits. Italian private insurers vary but often accept to age 80. The visa requires insurance, but after that, Italian public healthcare works regardless of age.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How do copays work for seniors?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">Those over 65 with income below certain thresholds (varies by region) are exempt from most SSN copays. This means doctor visits, many medications, and diagnostic tests are free. Apply for exemption (esenzione per età) at your local ASL.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the cost of living outside major cities?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">Italy varies dramatically. Tuscany: €2,000-3,000/month. Umbria/Le Marche: €1,500-2,000. Puglia/Calabria: €1,200-1,800. Southern regions offer significant savings while still providing good quality of life and SSN access.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready for La Dolce Vita?"
    description="Find insurance that meets visa requirements and transitions to Italian care."
    buttonText="Compare Plans →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This guide is for informational purposes. Italian visa requirements, SSN enrollment rules, and regional healthcare systems change. Verify current requirements with Italian consulates and local ASL offices. Consider consulting an immigration lawyer and connecting with expat communities in your target region.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
